# Next.js + TypeScript

## Rendering model

- Default to **Server Components**.
- Add `"use client"` only when needed (state, effects, browser APIs, event handlers).
- Push client boundaries down; keep data fetching on the server when possible.

## Mutations and data

- Prefer **Server Actions** or Route Handlers for mutations and privileged work.
- Do not call privileged APIs (Supabase service role, Firecrawl, DeepSeek) from Client Components.
- Colocate feature UI under `app/`; shared UI under `components/`; shared logic under `lib/`; shared types under `types/`.

## TypeScript

- Keep `strict` mode; avoid `any` (use `unknown` + narrowing).
- Prefer explicit return types on exported functions and shared utilities.
- Use path aliases: `@/components`, `@/lib`, `@/types`.

## Performance and UX

- Mobile-first layouts; touch targets and safe areas matter.
- Avoid unnecessary client JS; lazy-load heavy client-only pieces when useful.
- Handle loading / empty / error states explicitly for user flows.

## Readability

- Small focused modules over large catch-all files.
- Name files and exports by intent (`create-group-action.ts`, not `helpers2.ts`).
- Match existing project style (Prettier + ESLint); do not reformat unrelated files.
